--- PART 6: SIMPLER CHEBYSHEV RELATION ---
From the OEIS: Morgan-Voyce b(n,x) relates to Chebyshev via:
  b(n, x^2 - 2) = ... or
  b(n, t) = (1/sqrt(t+4)) * ((sqrt(t+4) + sqrt(t))/2)^{2n+1} + symm

Actually, let me just use the GF directly.
GF: sum_m b(m,x) z^m = (1-z)/((1-z)^2 - xz)
Setting z = 1/(t+1) might give the Q-polynomial generating function.

Key insight: Our polynomial P_m(t) = t^m * b(m, -1/t)
The ROOTS of P_m are Q_k = sin^2(pi*r(k)/p) / sin^2(pi*k/p)
These are given by Q_k = -1/(-1/Q_k) where b(m, -1/Q_k) = 0
So the ROOTS of b(m, -s) = 0 are s_k = 1/Q_k
And sum(s_k) = e_{m-1}/e_m = (p-2)/1 = p-2
This checks out: sum 1/Q_k = p-2 = 2m-1

--- PART 7: FIBONACCI IMPLICATIONS ---
Since e_j = C(m+j, 2j) and sum_j C(m+j, 2j) = F_{2m+1}:
  sum e_j = F_{2m+1}
This means: P_m(-1) = sum (-1)^j e_j * (-1)^{m-j} = (-1)^m * sum e_j = (-1)^m * F_{2m+1}
I.e., prod(1 + Q_k) = F_{2m+1} (up to sign)
  p=5, m=2: prod(1+Q_k) = 5.0000, F_5 = 5, match: True
  p=7, m=3: prod(1+Q_k) = 13.0000, F_7 = 13, match: True
  p=11, m=5: prod(1+Q_k) = 89.0000, F_11 = 89, match: True
  p=13, m=6: prod(1+Q_k) = 233.0000, F_13 = 233, match: True
  p=17, m=8: prod(1+Q_k) = 1597.0000, F_17 = 1597, match: True
  p=19, m=9: prod(1+Q_k) = 4181.0000, F_19 = 4181, match: True
  p=23, m=11: prod(1+Q_k) = 28657.0000, F_23 = 28657, match: True

--- PART 8: b(m, -4) = prod(Q_k - 4) * (-1)^m ---
P_m(4) = 4^m * b(m, -1/4)
This equals prod(4 - Q_k)
